Sure! Below is a simple web app example that includes HTML, CSS, and JavaScript all in a single file. This example creates a basic to-do list application where users can add and remove tasks.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>To-Do List App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333;
        }
        #taskInput {
            width: 80%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        #addTaskButton {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        #addTaskButton:hover {
            background-color: #218838;
        }
        #taskList {
            list-style-type: none;
            padding: 0;
        }
        .task {
            background: #fff;
            margin: 5px 0;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: space-between;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .removeTaskButton {
            background: #dc3545;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .removeTaskButton:hover {
            background: #c82333;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>To-Do List</h1>
    <input type="text" id="taskInput" placeholder="Add a new task...">
    <button id="addTaskButton">Add Task</button>
    <ul id="taskList"></ul>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('addTaskButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            const taskInput = document.getElementById('taskInput');
            const taskText = taskInput.value.trim();
            if (taskText) {
                const taskList = document.getElementById('taskList');
                const taskItem = document.createElement('li');
                taskItem.className = 'task';
                taskItem.innerHTML = `
                    ${taskText}
                    <button class="removeTaskButton">Remove</button>
                `;
                taskList.appendChild(taskItem);
                taskInput.value = '';

                taskItem.querySelector('.removeTaskButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
                    taskList.removeChild(taskItem);
                });
            }
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Paste it into a text editor and save it with a `.html` extension (e.g., `todo.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser.

### Features:
- Users can add tasks to the list.
- Each task has a "Remove" button to delete it from the list.
- The app is styled with basic CSS for a clean look.

Feel free to modify the styles and functionality as needed!
